    <li id="fn:11" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Josh Ellenbogen, ‚ÄúOn Photographic Elegy,‚Äù in Weisman, <em>Oxford
Handbook of the Elegy</em>, 676. Also helpful when thinking about the
temporality of the photographic image and its relationship to
mourning and loss is Susette Min, ‚ÄúRemains to Be Seen: Reading the
Works of Dean Sameshima and Khanh Vo,‚Äù in <em>Loss: The Politics of
Mourning</em>, ed. David L. Eng and David Kazanjian (Berkeley:
University of California Press, 2003), 229‚Äì50. ‚ÄúPhotography‚Äôs
privileged relation to melancholia,‚Äù Min claims, ‚Äúis in part one of
temporality‚Ä¶. The freezing of time creates a dimension in which the
future perfect of the photographic image‚Äîthis will-have-been‚Äîmay be
suspended, manipulated, and reworked to become the past perfected‚Äù
(241). And, I would add, the present.¬†<a href="#fnref:11" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:12" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Elizabeth Helsinger, ‚ÄúGrieving Images: Elegy and the Visual
Arts,‚Äù in Weisman, <em>Oxford Handbook of the Elegy</em>, 662.¬†<a href="#fnref:12" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:13" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Cemetery.org, the ‚ÄúWorld Wide Cemetery,‚Äù was created by Canadian
engineer and internet pioneer Mike Kibbee two years before his own
death from Hodgkin‚Äôs Lymphoma in 1995. For a one-time fee of $90, a
‚Äúpersonally customized, permanent memorial‚Äù can be linked to
relatives, merged with partners, and linked via a QR-Code to a
physical site of interment (‚ÄúHow It Works,‚Äù
<a href="https://cemetery.org/create-a-memorial/">https://cemetery.org/create-a-memorial/</a>). One can leave (vetted)
messages and photos and even virtual flowers (from a limited
selection). While I do not preclude Cemetery.org as a possible
digital node in digital diasporic elegiac practice, this essay makes
clear the differences between my foci and the elegiac work in which
the site engages. Cemetery.org formalizes grieving in ways that are
analogous to IRL (in real life) practices, from its business model
to its execution. To put it bluntly, it is not ‚Äúalive‚Äù but functions
more like a digital ossuary. At the time of this writing, it is not
a social media site with millions of active daily users and high
degrees of interactivity, nor has it been accessed by or included
memorials created for Caribbean subjects. It is not part of the
‚Äúdigital yard.‚Äù¬†<a href="#fnref:13" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:14" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>‚ÄúOzymandias,‚Äù a sonnet written in 1817 by Percy Bysshe Shelley
(1792‚Äì1822), condemns the hubris of those who build monuments in a
bid for immortality only to see them ravaged by time. It is believed
Shelley took his inspiration from a statue of Rameses II, and the
poem‚Äôs power lies in the image of a statue in ruins bearing the
words, ‚ÄúLook on my Works, ye Mighty, and despair!‚Äù Percy Bysshe
Shelley, ‚ÄúOzymandias,‚Äù <em>Examiner</em>, 11 January 1818
(<a href="https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/46565/Ozymandias">https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poems/46565/Ozymandias</a>).¬†<a href="#fnref:14" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
