    <li id="fn:33" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>I use the term <em>operationalize</em> to convey and retain for the
reader the relationship between a given word and its function in the
deep structure of both poetics and code. Code is a language
understood by computers. It is not a ‚Äúnatural language‚Äù per se,
despite human language being the symbolic system used to create it.
Human language has to be converted into a set of ‚Äúwords‚Äù that the
computer will understand. The keywords are akin to verbs. Verbs
describe or indicate action, and keywords initiate action. An
arrangement of keywords for successful execution of a desired
computation (or computational task) is referred to as <em>syntax</em>, and
when a set of keywords is put together with syntax, the result is a
programming language.¬†<a href="#fnref:33" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:34" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>Sandy Baldwin, ‚ÄúA Poem Is a Machine to Think With: Digital Poetry
and the Paradox of Innovation,‚Äù <em>Postmodern Culture</em> 13, no. 2
(2003), <a href="http://pmc.iath.virginia.edu/issue.103/13.2baldwin.html">http://pmc.iath.virginia.edu/issue.103/13.2baldwin.html</a>,
para. 13. Loss Peque√±o Glazier‚Äôs <em>Digital
Poetics: The Making of E-Poetries</em> (Tuscaloosa: University of
Alabama Press, 2002) was helpful in my distinguishing that I am not
referring to e-poetry, or solely literary texts that have been
migrated to digital environments.¬†<a href="#fnref:34" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:35" role="doc-endnote">
      <p>In fielding a question about the difference between clean and
messy code, Daniel Super claims that the key difference is
‚Äúcomprehensibility‚Äù: ‚ÄúYou can understand clean code when you read
it. It has meaningful variable and function names¬† The
responsibilities are separated out into discrete pieces. The methods
are organized in a manner that makes sense, with related
functionality grouped together. It has comments that actually help
you understand what‚Äôs happening. You can make sense of it. You don‚Äôt
have to read through it ten times and struggle to make sense of what
the person who wrote it was trying to do. Clean code is code that
someone else, other than the person who wrote it[,] could maintain
without wanting to strangle you and feed your corpse into a wood
chipper.‚Äù Daniel Super, ‚ÄúWhat Is the Biggest Difference between
‚ÄòClean Code‚Äô and ‚ÄòMessy Code‚Äô?,‚Äù <em>Quora</em>, 12 August 2015,
<a href="https://www.quora.com/What-is-the-biggest-difference-between-clean-code-and-messy-code">https://www.quora.com/What-is-the-biggest-difference-between-clean-code-and-messy-code</a>.¬†<a href="#fnref:35" class="reversefootnote" role="doc-backlink">&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;</a></p>
    </li>
    <li id="fn:36" role="doc-endnote">
